properties.Principal Architects: Francesco Laparelli, Michelangelo, Antonio da Sangallo the Elder, Raffaello Sinibaldi da Montelupo, Antonio da Sangallo the Younger
properties.Chronology: 130-139  Constructed as a mausoleum under Emperor Hadrian; 217  Last recorded burial; 401  Converted into a fortress and incorporated into the Aurelian Wall under Emperor Honorius; 410  Ransacked by the Visigoths; 520-530  Converted into a prison under Theodoric; 537  Used to defend the city during Gothic siege; 590  "Castel Sant’Angelo" after a vision of Archangel Michael marked the end of the plague under Gregory; 900-950  Acquired by Theophylact I; 950-1000  Acquired by the Crescenzi family "Castrum Crescentii"; 1277-1280  Passetto di Borgo constructed under Nicholas III to connect the building to St Peter's Basilica; 1395  Restored under Boniface IX; 1492-1503  Expanded by Antonio da Sangallo the Elder under Alexander VI; 1500-1600  Transformed into a papal palace; 1513-1521  Chapel constructed by Michelangelo (disputed) under Leo X; 1527  Served as a refuge for Clement VII during the Sack of Rome; 1542  Restored by Raffaello Sinibaldi da Montelupo and Antonio da Sangallo the Younger under Paul III; 1559-1565  Bastions constructed; 1630  Restored under Urban VIII; 1753  Topped with bronze statue constructed by Peter Anton von Verschaffelt; 1906  Transformed into the Museo dell'Ingegneria Militare;
properties.Principal Patrons: Hadrian, Emperor Honorius, Theodoric, Nicholas III, Boniface IX, Alexander VI, Leo X, Paul III, Urban VIII

properties.Chronology: 1559-1565  Constructed pentagonal walls (within which the chapel is housed) by Francesco Laparelli under Pius IV; 1849  Papal government lost control of the church during the uprising; 1870-1901  Castle transformed into a prison and church abandoned; 1930-1940  Destroyed for the Parco Adriano;
